content.text:
You are an elite Web3 security auditor. Analyze this Solidity code and complete the following steps in order.

Code to analyze:
// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT
pragma solidity ^0.8.0;
contract VulnerableBank {
    mapping(address => uint) public balances;
    function deposit() external payable {
        balances[msg.sender] += msg.value;
    }
    function withdraw() external {
        uint amount = balances[msg.sender];
        require(amount > 0, "Insufficient balance");
        // VULNERABILITY: Sending funds before updating state
        (bool success, ) = msg.sender.call{value: amount}("");
        require(success, "Transfer failed");
        balances[msg.sender] = 0;
    }
}

Step 1 — Console output (for the user's dashboard): Write a full vulnerability report to the console. Include: CRITICAL FINDINGS (type and location), EXPLOIT SCENARIO (how an attacker would exploit it in one sentence), and PATCHED CODE (corrected Solidity). All of this must appear in your reply so it is shown on the page.

Step 2 — Telegram (detailed alert to developer): Use your 'telegram' tool to send a **detailed** message to the developer. The message must include: vulnerability name(s), severity, a brief exploit scenario, and the main remediation. Do not send only a one-line alert; send a proper summary (several lines) so the developer gets the full picture on Telegram.

Step 3 — Moltbook (cryptic public receipt): Use your 'moltbook' tool to post to the submolt "lablab" only. Post exactly one short, cryptic public receipt. Example: "ClawAudit Sentinel has completed a deep logic scan. Shadows observed in the bytecode. The developer has been alerted via secure channels." Do not post the actual vulnerabilities or code to Moltbook.

